# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gomory-hu-tree
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] In graph theory, a **cut** is a partition of the vertices of a graph into two disjoint subsets.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] Any cut determines a **cut-set**, the set of edges that have one endpoint in each subset of the partition.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] These edges are said to **cross** the cut.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] In a connected graph, each cut-set determines a unique cut, and in some cases cuts are identified with their cut-sets rather than with their vertex partitions.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] In a flow network, an **s–t cut** is a cut that requires the *source* and the *sink* to be in different subsets, and its *cut-set* only consists of edges going from the source's side to the sink's side.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] The *capacity* of an s–t cut is defined as the sum of the capacity of each edge in the *cut-set*.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] A **cut** *C* = (*S*, *T*) is a partition of V of a graph *G* = (*V*, *E*) into two subsets S and T.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] The **cut-set** of a cut *C* = (*S*, *T*) is the set {(*u*, *v*) ∈ *E* | *u* ∈ *S*, *v* ∈ *T*} of edges that have one endpoint in S and the other endpoint in T.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] If s and t are specified vertices of the graph G, then an **s–t cut** is a cut in which s belongs to the set S and t belongs to the set T.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] In an unweighted undirected graph, the *size* or *weight* of a cut is the number of edges crossing the cut.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] In a weighted graph, the **value** or **weight** is defined by the sum of the weights of the edges crossing the cut.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] A **bond** is a cut-set that does not have any other cut-set as a proper subset.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] A cut is *minimum* if the size or weight of the cut is not larger than the size of any other cut.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] The illustration on the right shows a minimum cut: the size of this cut is 2, and there is no cut of size 1 because the graph is bridgeless.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] The max-flow min-cut theorem proves that the maximum network flow and the sum of the cut-edge weights of any minimum cut that separates the source and the sink are equal.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] There are polynomial-time methods to solve the min-cut problem, notably the Edmonds–Karp algorithm.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] A cut is *maximum* if the size of the cut is not smaller than the size of any other cut.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] The illustration on the right shows a maximum cut: the size of the cut is equal to 5, and there is no cut of size 6, or |*E*| (the number of edges), because the graph is not bipartite (there is an odd cycle).
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] In general, finding a maximum cut is computationally hard.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] The max-cut problem is one of Karp's 21 NP-complete problems.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] The max-cut problem is also APX-hard, meaning that there is no polynomial-time approximation scheme for it unless P = NP.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] However, it can be approximated to within a constant approximation ratio using semidefinite programming.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] Note that min-cut and max-cut are *not* dual problems in the linear programming sense, even though one gets from one problem to other by changing min to max in the objective function.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] The max-flow problem is the dual of the min-cut problem.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] The **sparsest cut problem** is to bipartition the vertices so as to minimize the ratio of the number of edges across the cut divided by the number of vertices in the smaller half of the partition.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] This objective function favors solutions that are both sparse (few edges crossing the cut) and balanced (close to a bisection).
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] The problem is known to be NP-hard, and the best known approximation algorithm is an $O({\sqrt {\log n}})$ approximation due to Arora, Rao & Vazirani (2009).
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] The family of all cut sets of an undirected graph is known as the **cut space** of the graph.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] It forms a vector space over the two-element finite field of arithmetic modulo two, with the symmetric difference of two cut sets as the vector addition operation, and is the orthogonal complement of the cycle space.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] If the edges of the graph are given positive weights, the minimum weight basis of the cut space can be described by a tree on the same vertex set as the graph, called the Gomory–Hu tree.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/cut-graph-theory] Each edge of this tree is associated with a bond in the original graph, and the minimum cut between two nodes *s* and *t* is the minimum weight bond among the ones associated with the path from *s* to *t* in the tree.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] In graph theory, a **flow network** (also known as a **transportation network**) is a directed graph where each edge has a **capacity** and each edge receives a flow.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] The amount of flow on an edge cannot exceed the capacity of the edge.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] Often in operations research, a directed graph is called a **network**, the vertices are called **nodes** and the edges are called **arcs**.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] A flow must satisfy the restriction that the amount of flow into a node equals the amount of flow out of it, unless it is a **source**, which has only outgoing flow, or **sink**, which has only incoming flow.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] A flow network can be used to model traffic in a computer network, circulation with demands, fluids in pipes, currents in an electrical circuit, or anything similar in which something travels through a network of nodes.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] As such, efficient algorithms for solving network flows can also be applied to solve problems that can be reduced to a flow network, including survey design, airline scheduling, image segmentation, and the matching problem.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] A **network** is a directed graph *G* = (*V*, *E*) with a non-negative **capacity** function *c* for each edge, and without multiple arcs (i.e. edges with the same source and target nodes).
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] Without loss of generality, we may assume that if (*u*, *v*) ∈ *E*, then (*v*, *u*) is also a member of E.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] If two nodes in G are distinguished – one as the source s and the other as the sink t – then (*G*, *c*, *s*, *t*) is called a **flow network**.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] In flow networks, the source s is deficient, and the sink t is active.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] Pseudo-flows, feasible flows, and pre-flows are all examples of flow functions.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] The **value** |*f*| of a feasible flow f for a network, is the net flow into the sink t of the flow network, that is: |*f*| = *x**f* (*t*).
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] Note, the flow value in a network is also equal to the total outgoing flow of source s, that is: |*f*| = −*x**f* (*s*).
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] Also, if we define *A* as a set of nodes in *G* such that *s* ∈ *A* and *t* ∉ *A*, the flow value is equal to the total net flow going out of A (i.e. |*f*| = *f* out(*A*) − *f* in(*A*)).
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] The flow value in a network is the total amount of flow from s to t.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] Flow decomposition is a process of breaking down a given flow into a collection of path flows and cycle flows.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] Every flow through a network can be decomposed into one or more paths and corresponding quantities, such that each edge in the flow equals the sum of all quantities of paths that pass through it.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] Flow decomposition is a powerful tool in optimization problems to maximize or minimize specific flow parameters.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] We do not use multiple arcs within a network because we can combine those arcs into a single arc.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] Along with the other constraints, the skew symmetry constraint must be remembered during this step to maintain the direction of the original pseudo-flow arc.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] Adding flow to an arc is the same as adding an arc with the capacity of zero.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] The **residual capacity** of an arc e with respect to a pseudo-flow f is denoted *c**f*, and it is the difference between the arc's capacity and its flow.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] From this we can construct a **residual network**, denoted *G**f* (*V*, *E**f*), with a capacity function *c**f* which models the amount of *available* capacity on the set of arcs in *G* = (*V*, *E*).
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] More specifically, capacity function *c**f* of each arc (*u*, *v*) in the residual network represents the amount of flow which can be transferred from u to v given the current state of the flow within the network.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] This concept is used in Ford–Fulkerson algorithm which computes the maximum flow in a flow network.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] Note that there can be an unsaturated path (a path with available capacity) from u to v in the residual network, even though there is no such path from u to v in the original network.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] Since flows in opposite directions cancel out, *decreasing* the flow from v to u is the same as *increasing* the flow from u to v.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] More simply, an augmenting path is an available flow path from the source to the sink.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] A network is at maximum flow if and only if there is no augmenting path in the residual network *G**f*.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] The **bottleneck** is the minimum residual capacity of all the edges in a given augmenting path.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] See example explained in the "Example" section of this article.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] The flow network is at maximum flow if and only if it has a bottleneck with a value equal to zero.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] If any augmenting path exists, its bottleneck weight will be greater than 0.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] In other words, if there is a bottleneck value greater than 0, then there is an augmenting path from the source to the sink.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] However, we know that if there is any augmenting path, then the network is not at maximum flow, which in turn means that, if there is a bottleneck value greater than 0, then the network is not at maximum flow.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] The term "augmenting the flow" for an augmenting path means updating the flow f of each arc in this augmenting path to equal the capacity *c* of the bottleneck.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] Augmenting the flow corresponds to pushing additional flow along the augmenting path until there is no remaining available residual capacity in the bottleneck.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] Sometimes, when modeling a network with more than one source, a **supersource** is introduced to the graph.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] This consists of a vertex connected to each of the sources with edges of infinite capacity, so as to act as a global source.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] A similar construct for sinks is called a **supersink**.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] In Figure 1 you see a flow network with source labeled s, sink t, and four additional nodes.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] The flow and capacity is denoted $f/c$ .
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] Notice how the network upholds the capacity constraint and flow conservation constraint.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] The total amount of flow from s to t is 5, which can be easily seen from the fact that the total outgoing flow from s is 5, which is also the incoming flow to t.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] By the skew symmetry constraint, from c to a is -2 because the flow from a to c is 2.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] In Figure 2 you see the residual network for the same given flow.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] Notice how there is positive residual capacity on some edges where the original capacity is zero in Figure 1, for example for the edge $(d,c)$ .
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] There is available capacity along the paths $(s,a,c,t)$ , $(s,a,b,d,t)$ and $(s,a,b,d,c,t)$ , which are then the augmenting paths.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] Picture a series of water pipes, fitting into a network.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] Each pipe is of a certain diameter, so it can only maintain a flow of a certain amount of water.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] Anywhere that pipes meet, the total amount of water coming into that junction must be equal to the amount going out, otherwise we would quickly run out of water, or we would have a buildup of water.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] We have a water inlet, which is the source, and an outlet, the sink.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] A flow would then be one possible way for water to get from source to sink so that the total amount of water coming out of the outlet is consistent.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] Intuitively, the total flow of a network is the rate at which water comes out of the outlet.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] Flows can pertain to people or material over transportation networks, or to electricity over electrical distribution systems.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] For any such physical network, the flow coming into any intermediate node needs to equal the flow going out of that node.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] This conservation constraint is equivalent to Kirchhoff's current law.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] Flow networks also find applications in ecology: flow networks arise naturally when considering the flow of nutrients and energy between different organisms in a food web.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] The mathematical problems associated with such networks are quite different from those that arise in networks of fluid or traffic flow.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] The field of ecosystem network analysis, developed by Robert Ulanowicz and others, involves using concepts from information theory and thermodynamics to study the evolution of these networks over time.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] The simplest and most common problem using flow networks is to find what is called the maximum flow, which provides the largest possible total flow from the source to the sink in a given graph.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] There are many other problems which can be solved using max flow algorithms, if they are appropriately modeled as flow networks, such as bipartite matching, the assignment problem and the transportation problem.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] Maximum flow problems can be solved in polynomial time with various algorithms (see table).
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] The max-flow min-cut theorem states that finding a maximal network flow is equivalent to finding a cut of minimum capacity that separates the source and the sink, where a cut is the division of vertices such that the source is in one division and the sink is in another.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] In a multi-commodity flow problem, you have multiple sources and sinks, and various "commodities" which are to flow from a given source to a given sink.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] This could be for example various goods that are produced at various factories, and are to be delivered to various given customers through the *same* transportation network.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] In a minimum cost flow problem, each edge $u,v$ has a given cost $k(u,v)$ , and the cost of sending the flow $f(u,v)$ across the edge is $f(u,v)\cdot k(u,v)$ .
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] The objective is to send a given amount of flow from the source to the sink, at the lowest possible price.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] In a circulation problem, you have a lower bound $\ell (u,v)$ on the edges, in addition to the upper bound $c(u,v)$ .
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] Often, flow conservation holds for *all* nodes in a circulation problem, and there is a connection from the sink back to the source.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] In this way, you can dictate the total flow with $\ell (t,s)$ and $c(t,s)$ .
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] The flow *circulates* through the network, hence the name of the problem.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] In a **network with gains** or **generalized network** each edge has a **gain**, a real number (not zero) such that, if the edge has gain *g*, and an amount *x* flows into the edge at its tail, then an amount *gx* flows out at the head.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] In a **source localization problem**, an algorithm tries to identify the most likely source node of information diffusion through a partially observed network.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/flow-network] This can be done in linear time for trees and cubic time for arbitrary networks and has applications ranging from tracking mobile phone users to identifying the originating source of disease outbreaks.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/gomory-hu-tree] In combinatorial optimization, the **Gomory–Hu tree** of an undirected graph with capacities is a weighted tree that represents the minimum *s*-*t* cuts for all *s*-*t* pairs in the graph.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/gomory-hu-tree] The Gomory–Hu tree can be constructed in |*V*| − 1 maximum flow computations.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/gomory-hu-tree] Let $G=(V_{G},E_{G},c)$ be an undirected graph with $c(u,v)$ being the capacity of the edge $(u,v)$ respectively.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/gomory-hu-tree] Choose some $X\in V_{T}$ with |*X*| ≥ 2 if such X exists.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/gomory-hu-tree] Using the submodular property of the capacity function c, one has $c(X)+c(Y)\geq c(X\cap Y)+c(X\cup Y).$ Then it can be shown that the minimum *s*-*t* cut in G' is also a minimum *s*-*t* cut in G for any *s*, *t* ∈ *X*.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/gomory-hu-tree] The lemma can be used again repeatedly to show that the output T satisfies the properties of a Gomory–Hu Tree.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/gomory-hu-tree] *red* and *blue* circles are the vertices in *G*'.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/gomory-hu-tree] *grey* vertices are the chosen *s* and *t*.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/gomory-hu-tree] *red* and *blue* coloring represents the *s*-*t* cut.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/gomory-hu-tree] *A* is the set of vertices circled in *red* and *B* is the set of vertices circled in *blue*.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/gomory-hu-tree] Gusfield's algorithm can be used to find a Gomory–Hu tree without any vertex contraction in the same running time-complexity, which simplifies the implementation of constructing a Gomory–Hu Tree.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/gomory-hu-tree] Tsioutsiouliklis implemented the Gomory-Hu algorithm and Gusfield algorithm, and performed an experimental evaluation and comparison.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/gomory-hu-tree] Cohen et al. report results on two parallel implementations of Gusfield's algorithm using OpenMP and MPI, respectively.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/gomory-hu-tree] In planar graphs, the Gomory–Hu tree is dual to the minimum weight cycle basis, in the sense that the cuts of the Gomory–Hu tree are dual to a collection of cycles in the dual graph that form a minimum-weight cycle basis.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] For example, imagine a network of pipes carrying water from a reservoir (the source) to a city (the sink).
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Each pipe has a capacity representing the maximum amount of water that can flow through it per unit of time.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The max-flow min-cut theorem tells us that the maximum amount of water that can reach the city is limited by the smallest total capacity of any set of pipes that, if cut, would completely isolate the reservoir from the city.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] This smallest total capacity is the min-cut.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] So, if there's a bottleneck in the pipe network, represented by a small min-cut, that bottleneck will determine the overall maximum flow of water to the city.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] This is a special case of the duality theorem for linear programs and can be used to derive Menger's theorem and the Kőnig–Egerváry theorem.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The theorem equates two quantities: the maximum flow through a network, and the minimum capacity of a cut of the network.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] To state the theorem, each of these notions must first be defined.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] A flow can be visualized as a physical flow of a fluid through the network, following the direction of each edge.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] where as above s is the source and t is the sink of the network.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] In the fluid analogy, it represents the amount of fluid entering the network at the source.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Because of the conservation axiom for flows, this is the same as the amount of flow leaving the network at the sink.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The maximum flow problem asks for the largest flow on a given network.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The other half of the max-flow min-cut theorem refers to a different aspect of a network: the collection of cuts.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] That is, an *s*-*t* cut is a division of the vertices of the network into two parts, with the source in one part and the sink in the other.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Thus, if all the edges in the cut-set of C are removed, then no positive flow is possible, because there is no path in the resulting graph from the source to the sink.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] There are typically many cuts in a graph, but cuts with smaller weights are often more difficult to find.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] such that the capacity of the s-t cut is minimal.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] In the above situation, one can prove that the value of any flow through a network is less than or equal to the capacity of any *s-t* cut, and that furthermore a flow with maximal value and a cut with minimal capacity exist.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The main theorem links the maximum flow value with the minimum cut capacity of the network.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The maximum value of an s-t flow is equal to the minimum capacity over all s-t cuts.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The figure on the right shows a flow in a network.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The numerical annotation on each arrow, in the form *f*/*c*, indicates the flow (*f*) and the capacity (*c*) of the arrow.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The flows emanating from the source total five (2+3=5), as do the flows into the sink (2+3=5), establishing that the flow's value is 5.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The capacities of the edges that cross this cut are 3 and 2, giving a cut capacity of 3+2=5.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The value of the flow is equal to the capacity of the cut, showing that the flow is a maximal flow and the cut is a minimal cut.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Note that the flow through each of the two arrows that connect *S* to *T* is at full capacity; this is always the case: a minimal cut represents a 'bottleneck' of the system.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The max-flow problem and min-cut problem can be formulated as two primal-dual linear programs.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The dual LP is obtained using the algorithm described in dual linear program: the variables and sign constraints of the dual correspond to the constraints of the primal, and the constraints of the dual correspond to the variables and sign constraints of the primal.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The resulting LP requires some explanation.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The minimization objective sums the capacity over all the edges that are contained in the cut.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Note that, since this is a minimization problem, we do not have to guarantee that an edge is *not* in the cut - we only have to guarantee that each edge that should be in the cut, is summed in the objective function.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The maximum flow problem can be formulated as the maximization of the electrical current through a network composed of nonlinear resistive elements.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] In this formulation, the limit of the current *I*in between the input terminals of the electrical network as the input voltage *V*in approaches $\infty$ , is equal to the weight of the minimum-weight cut set.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] In other words, the amount of *flow* passing through a vertex cannot exceed its capacity.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Define an *s-t cut* to be the set of vertices and edges such that for any path from *s* to *t*, the path contains a member of the cut.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] In this case, the *capacity of the cut* is the sum of the capacity of each edge and vertex in it.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] In this new definition, the **generalized max-flow min-cut theorem** states that the maximum value of an s-t flow is equal to the minimum capacity of an s-t cut in the new sense.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] In the undirected edge-disjoint paths problem, we are given an undirected graph *G* = (*V*, *E*) and two vertices s and t, and we have to find the maximum number of edge-disjoint s-t paths in G.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] In the project selection problem, there are n projects and m machines.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Each project pi yields revenue *r*(*pi*) and each machine qj costs *c*(*qj*) to purchase.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] We want to select a subset of the project, and purchase a subset of the machines, to maximize the total profit (revenue of the selected projects minus cost of the purchased machines).
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] We must obey the following constraint: each project specifies a set of machines which must be purchased if the project is selected.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The above minimization problem can then be formulated as a minimum-cut problem by constructing a network, where the source is connected to the projects with capacity *r*(*pi*), and the sink is connected by the machines with capacity *c*(*qj*).
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] An edge (*pi*, *qj*) with *infinite* capacity is added if project pi requires machine qj.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The s-t cut-set represents the projects and machines in P and Q respectively.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] By the max-flow min-cut theorem, one can solve the problem as a maximum flow problem.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The minimum capacity of an s-t cut is 250 and the sum of the revenue of each project is 450; therefore the maximum profit *g* is 450 − 250 = 200, by selecting projects *p*2 and *p*3.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The idea here is to 'flow' each project's profits through the 'pipes' of its machines.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] If we cannot fill the pipe from a machine, the machine's return is less than its cost, and the min cut algorithm will find it cheaper to cut the project's profit edge instead of the machine's cost edge.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] In the image segmentation problem, there are n pixels.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Each pixel i can be assigned a foreground value fi or a background value bi.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] There is a penalty of pij if pixels i, j are adjacent and have different assignments.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The problem is to assign pixels to foreground or background such that the sum of their values minus the penalties is maximum.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The above minimization problem can be formulated as a minimum-cut problem by constructing a network where the source (orange node) is connected to all the pixels with capacity fi, and the sink (purple node) is connected by all the pixels with capacity bi.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Two edges (i, j) and (j, i) with pij capacity are added between two adjacent pixels.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] The s-t cut-set then represents the pixels assigned to the foreground in P and pixels assigned to background in Q.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] "Determining a maximal steady state flow from one point to another in a network subject to capacity limitations on arcs ... was posed to the authors in the spring of 1955 by T.E.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Harris, who, in conjunction with General F.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Ross (Ret.) had formulated a simplified model of railway traffic flow, and pinpointed this particular problem as the central one suggested by the model.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] It was not long after this until the main result, Theorem 5.1, which we call the max-flow min-cut theorem, was conjectured and established.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Let *G* = (*V*, *E*) be a network (directed graph) with s and t being the source and the sink of G respectively.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Consider the flow *f* computed for G by Ford–Fulkerson algorithm.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Now, we know, $value(f)=f_{out}(A)-f_{in}(A)$ for any subset of vertices, A.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Both of the above statements prove that the capacity of cut obtained in the above described manner is equal to the flow obtained in the network.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Also, the flow was obtained by Ford-Fulkerson algorithm, so it is the max-flow of the network as well.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] Also, since any flow in the network is always less than or equal to capacity of every cut possible in a network, the above described cut is also the min-cut which obtains the max-flow.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/max-flow-min-cut-theorem] A corollary from this proof is that the maximum flow through any set of edges in a cut of a graph is equal to the minimum capacity of all previous cuts.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/minimum-cut] In graph theory, a **minimum cut** or **min-cut** of a graph is a cut (a partition of the vertices of a graph into two disjoint subsets) that is minimal in some metric.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/minimum-cut] In the simplest *unweighted min-cut problem*, the goal is to minimize the number of edges connecting the two parts.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/minimum-cut] Variations of the minimum cut problem consider *weighted graphs*, *directed graphs*, *terminals*, and partitioning the vertices into *more than two sets*.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/minimum-cut] The weighted min-cut problem allowing both positive and negative weights can be trivially transformed into a weighted maximum cut problem by flipping the sign in all weights.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/minimum-cut] The required output is a partition V = S + T (a partition of the vertices into two disjoint subsets S and T).
[src:gomory-hu-tree/minimum-cut] Any such partition has a *cost,* and the goal is to find a partition with a smallest cost.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/minimum-cut] A generalization of the minimum cut problem without terminals is the minimum k-cut, in which the goal is to partition the graph into at least k connected components by removing as few edges as possible.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/minimum-cut] For a fixed value of k, this problem can be solved in polynomial time, though the algorithm is not practical for large k.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/minimum-cut] In the variant called *min s-t cut*, the input contains, in addition to the graph, two nodes called *s* (source) and *t* (target / sink).
[src:gomory-hu-tree/minimum-cut] The required output is a partition V = S + T such that s is in S and t is in T.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/minimum-cut] In a flow network, the minimum cut separates the source and sink vertices and minimizes the total sum of the capacities of the edges that are directed from the source side of the cut to the sink side of the cut.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/minimum-cut] As shown in the max-flow min-cut theorem, the weight of this cut equals the maximum amount of flow that can be sent from the source to the sink in the given network.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/minimum-cut] In a weighted, undirected network, it is possible to calculate the cut that separates a particular pair of vertices from each other and has minimum possible total cost.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/minimum-cut] A system of cuts that solves this problem for every possible vertex pair can be collected into a structure known as the Gomory–Hu tree of the graph.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/minimum-cut] A generalization of the minimum cut problem with terminals is the k-terminal cut, or multi-terminal cut.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/minimum-cut] In a planar graph, this problem can be solved in polynomial time.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/minimum-cut] However, in general this problem is NP-hard, even for $k=3$ .
[src:gomory-hu-tree/minimum-cut] Graph partition problems are a family of combinatorial optimization problems in which a graph is to be partitioned into two or more parts with additional constraints such as balancing the sizes of the two sides of the cut.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/minimum-cut] Segmentation-based object categorization can be viewed as a specific case of normalized min-cut spectral clustering applied to image segmentation.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/minimum-cut] It can also be used as a generic clustering method, where the nodes are data samples assumed to be taken from a metric space and edge weights are their distances.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/minimum-cut] This is however often impractical due do the high computational complexity for $k>2$ .
[src:gomory-hu-tree/minimum-cut] Due to max-flow min-cut theorem, 2 nodes' Minimum cut value is equal to their maxflow value.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/minimum-cut] In this case, some algorithms used in maxflow problem could also be used to solve this question.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/minimum-cut] A graph with n vertices can at the most have ${\binom {n}{2}}={\frac {n(n-1)}{2}}$ distinct minimum cuts.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/minimum-cut] This bound is tight in the sense that a (simple) cycle on n vertices has exactly ${\frac {n(n-1)}{2}}$ minimum cuts.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] In graph theory, a **tree** is an undirected graph in which every pair of distinct vertices is connected by *exactly one* path, or equivalently, a connected acyclic undirected graph.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] A **forest** is an undirected graph in which any two vertices are connected by *at most one* path, or equivalently an acyclic undirected graph, or equivalently a disjoint union of trees.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] A directed tree, oriented tree, polytree, or singly connected network is a directed acyclic graph (DAG) whose underlying undirected graph is a tree.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] A polyforest (or directed forest or oriented forest) is a directed acyclic graph whose underlying undirected graph is a forest.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] The various kinds of data structures referred to as trees in computer science have underlying graphs that are trees in graph theory, although such data structures are generally rooted trees.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] A rooted tree may be directed, called a directed rooted tree, either making all its edges point away from the root—in which case it is called an arborescence or out-tree—or making all its edges point towards the root—in which case it is called an anti-arborescence or in-tree.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] A rooted tree itself has been defined by some authors as a directed graph.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] A rooted forest is a disjoint union of rooted trees.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] The term *tree* was coined in 1857 by the British mathematician Arthur Cayley.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] It may, however, be considered as a forest consisting of zero trees.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] An *internal vertex* (or inner vertex) is a vertex of degree at least 2.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] Similarly, an *external vertex* (or outer vertex, terminal vertex or leaf) is a vertex of degree 1.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] A branch vertex in a tree is a vertex of degree at least 3.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] An *irreducible tree* (or series-reduced tree) is a tree in which there is no vertex of degree 2 (enumerated at sequence A000014 in the OEIS).
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] A *forest* is an undirected acyclic graph or equivalently a disjoint union of trees.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] Trivially so, each connected component of a forest is a tree.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] As special cases, the order-zero graph (a forest consisting of zero trees), a single tree, and an edgeless graph, are examples of forests.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] Since for every tree *V* − *E* = 1, we can easily count the number of trees that are within a forest by subtracting the difference between total vertices and total edges.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] *V* − *E* = number of trees in a forest.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] A *polytree* (or *directed tree* or *oriented tree* or *singly connected network*) is a directed acyclic graph (DAG) whose underlying undirected graph is a tree.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] In other words, if we replace its directed edges with undirected edges, we obtain an undirected graph that is both connected and acyclic.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] Some authors restrict the phrase "directed tree" to the case where the edges are all directed towards a particular vertex, or all directed away from a particular vertex (see arborescence).
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] A *polyforest* (or directed forest or oriented forest) is a directed acyclic graph whose underlying undirected graph is a forest.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] In other words, if we replace its directed edges with undirected edges, we obtain an undirected graph that is acyclic.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] As with directed trees, some authors restrict the phrase "directed forest" to the case where the edges of each connected component are all directed towards a particular vertex, or all directed away from a particular vertex (see branching).
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] A *rooted tree* is a tree in which one vertex has been designated the root.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] The edges of a rooted tree can be assigned a natural orientation, either away from or towards the root, in which case the structure becomes a directed rooted tree.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] When a directed rooted tree has an orientation away from the root, it is called an *arborescence* or *out-tree*; when it has an orientation towards the root, it is called an *anti-arborescence* or *in-tree*.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] The tree-order is the partial ordering on the vertices of a tree with *u* < *v* only if the unique path from the root to v passes through u.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] A rooted tree T that is a subgraph of some graph G is a normal tree if the ends of every T-path in G are comparable in this tree-order (Diestel 2005, p.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] Rooted trees, often with an additional structure such as an ordering of the neighbors at each vertex, are a key data structure in computer science; see tree data structure.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] In a context where trees typically have a root, a tree without any designated root is called a *free tree*.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] A *labeled tree* is a tree in which each vertex is given a unique label.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] The vertices of a labeled tree on n vertices (for nonnegative integers n) are typically given the labels 1, 2, …, *n*.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] A *recursive tree* is a labeled rooted tree where the vertex labels respect the tree order (i.e., if *u* < *v* for two vertices u and v, then the label of u is smaller than the label of v).
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] In a rooted tree, the **parent** of a vertex v is the vertex connected to v on the path to the root; every vertex has a unique parent, except the root has no parent.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] A *child* of a vertex v is a vertex of which v is the parent.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] An *ascendant* of a vertex v is any vertex that is either the parent of v or is (recursively) an ascendant of a parent of v.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] A *descendant* of a vertex v is any vertex that is either a child of v or is (recursively) a descendant of a child of v.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] A *sibling* to a vertex v is any other vertex on the tree that shares a parent with v.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] An *internal vertex* is a vertex that is not a leaf.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] The *height* of a vertex in a rooted tree is the length of the longest downward path to a leaf from that vertex.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] The *height* of the tree is the height of the root.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] The *depth* of a vertex is the length of the path to its root (*root path*).
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] The depth of a tree is the maximum depth of any vertex.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] Depth is commonly needed in the manipulation of the various self-balancing trees, AVL trees in particular.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] The root has depth zero, leaves have height zero, and a tree with only a single vertex (hence both a root and leaf) has depth and height zero.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] Conventionally, an empty tree (a tree with no vertices, if such are allowed) has depth and height −1.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] A *k-ary tree* (for nonnegative integers k) is a rooted tree in which each vertex has at most k children.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] 2-ary trees are often called *binary trees*, while 3-ary trees are sometimes called *ternary trees*.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] An *ordered tree* (alternatively, *plane tree* or *positional tree*) is a rooted tree in which an ordering is specified for the children of each vertex.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] This is called a "plane tree" because an ordering of the children is equivalent to an embedding of the tree in the plane, with the root at the top and the children of each vertex lower than that vertex.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] Given an embedding of a rooted tree in the plane, if one fixes a direction of children, say left to right, then an embedding gives an ordering of the children.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] Conversely, given an ordered tree, and conventionally drawing the root at the top, then the child vertices in an ordered tree can be drawn left-to-right, yielding an essentially unique planar embedding.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] Cayley's formula states that there are *n**n*−2 trees on n labeled vertices.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] A more general problem is to count spanning trees in an undirected graph, which is addressed by the matrix tree theorem.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] (Cayley's formula is the special case of spanning trees in a complete graph.) The similar problem of counting all the subtrees regardless of size is #P-complete in the general case (Jerrum (1994)).
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] Counting the number of unlabeled free trees is a harder problem.
[src:gomory-hu-tree/tree-graph-theory] No closed formula for the number *t*(*n*) of trees with n vertices up to graph isomorphism is known.
